04567nam a22007215i 9780823290734DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232907347 a10.1515/97808232907342doi  a(DE-B1597)565956  a(OCoLC)1306540374  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360602bisacsh02aA Coat of Many Colors :bImmigration, Globalization, and Reform in New York City's Garment Industry /ced. by Daniel Soyer. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than a century and a half—from the middle of the 19th century to the end of the 20th—the garment industry was the largest manufacturing industry in New York City, and New York made more clothes than anywhere else. For generations, the industry employed more New Yorkers than any other and was central to the city’s history, culture, and identity. Today, although no longer the big heart of industrial New York, the needle trades are still an important part of the city’s economy—especially for the new waves of immigrants who cut, sew, and assemble clothing in shops around the five boroughs. In this valuable book, historians, sociologists, and economists explore the rise and fall of the garment industry and its impact on New York and its people, as part of a global process of economic change. Essays trace the rise of the industry, from the creation of a Manhattan garment district employing immigrants from nearby enements to the contemporary spread of Chinese-owned shops in cheaper neighborhoods. The tumultuous history of workers and their bosses is the focus of chapters on contractors and labor militants and on the experiences of Italian, Chinese, Jewish, Dominican, and other ethnic workers. The final chapter looks at air labor, social responsibility, and the political economy of the offshore garment industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aAbram, Ruth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBao, Xiaolan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoris, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarnevale, Nancy C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Margaret M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Nancy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosak, Hadassa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalpacuer, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoyer, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoyer, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329073440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823290734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823290734/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK